::Crisis Definition::According to lecture, what are the THREE essential characteristics that define a business crisis?{
=Threat to organization, surprise element, short decision time #Lecture defined a crisis using exactly these three characteristics\: (1) Threat to organization - significant potential for negative consequences; (2) Surprise element - often unexpected with limited decision time; (3) Short decision time - requires rapid response. This definition was presented on Slide 7 with the formula "Crisis \= Threat + Surprise + Short Time."
~Financial loss, media attention, stakeholder anger #These are potential OUTCOMES of crises, not defining characteristics. Not all crises involve financial loss or media attention.
~Legal liability, reputation damage, employee turnover #These are consequences, not defining features. Crises can occur without legal liability or employee turnover.
~Social media backlash, customer complaints, competitor attacks #These are modern crisis manifestations, but don't define what makes something a crisis vs. a regular problem.
}

::Argenti's Framework::Which of Argenti's crisis communication principles states that internal employee communication must precede all external announcements?{
~Get on the Scene #"Get on the Scene" refers to leadership visibility during crises, not communication sequencing.
~Choose Your Channels Carefully #"Choose Your Channels Carefully" is about using multiple communication channels (voice mail, website, social media), not who to communicate with first.
=Communicate with Employees First #Argenti's Principle 3 explicitly states "Communicate with Employees First" - internal employee communication must precede all external announcements. This was emphasized on Slide 9 and reinforced throughout lecture with the quote "Organizations face 'a human crisis' requiring focus on people before customers or investors."
~Have a Plan in Place #"Have a Plan in Place" refers to crisis preparedness (contingency sites, backup communication infrastructure), not communication order.
}

